\section{Process Description}
\subsection{Operating Principles}

There are three essential operating principles that make this particular
Gem paperclip design effective towards the purpose of temporarily
attaching papers together. First, the elastic spring metal of the paperclip
allows its clip-ends to be expanded, and then contract back into place. This
dynamic is represented by Hooke's Law, which essentially states that the
extension of a spring is proportional to the force applied to that spring. The end result
is two clip-ends that retract towards each other, attaching any papers that sit
between their grip. The second property that makes the paperclip an effective
tool is friction. The paperclip's vinyl-clad metal finish makes it
coarse enough to provide sufficient friction for holding papers together, while
smooth enough to not be abrasive as papers are slipped into, and out of its
grip. Finally, the offset length of its clip-ends makes inserting a stack of
papers into a paperclip more seamless. As seen in Figure
\ref{fig:paperclip_use}, offset clip-ends allows papers to rest on the longer-end,
while being easily slipped beneath the clasping grip of the shorter-end.

